  "texts": [
    "This methodological evolution aligns with a broader emphasis on quantifying morphological variability and evolutionary trends using automated techniques.",
    "DL models have facilitated the detection of subtle morphological variations that traditional manual classification might overlook due to smaller sample sizes, enabling more nuanced taxonomic resolution.",
    "This is particularly valuable in clades with high morphological disparity or convergent evolution.",
    "For example, DL-based quantitative assessments of mimicry in fossil insects have provided new insights into the ecological and evolutionary implications of mimicry patterns (Fan et al. 2022).",
    "Similarly, automated classification of vertebrate teeth has advanced studies on dietary evolution and adaptive radiations, deepening our understanding of how morphological traits correlate with ecological niches over time."
